<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-sensitivity">
	<title>Sensitivity to change</title>

	<objectives>
		<ol>
			<li>
				<p>
					Measure a function's responsiveness to small changes using ratios.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Visualize the sensitivity of a function as a ratio of differentials.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Use the sign and value of the sensitivity to estimate changes in the dependent variable.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ol>
	</objectives>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Calculus is often described as the mathematics of change. Many quantities in the world change in tandem with each other:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					The pressure of a gas depends on its temperature and volume.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The demand for a product depends on its price.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The daily calories needed by an organism depends on its mass.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The speed of a car depends on the pressure applied to the gas pedal.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The growth of a bacterial population depends on the amount of nutrients available.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The amount of traffic congestion depends on the number of cars on the road.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The brightness of a lamp depends on the electrical power supplied to it.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The time for a computer to sort a list depends on the number of items in the list.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			To understand these relationships, we need a way to quantify how <em>sensitive</em> one quantity is to changes in another: if we change one variable by a small amount, how much does another variable change in response?
		</p>
	</introduction>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-introduction-to-sensitivity">
        <title>Introduction to sensitivity</title>
        <p>
            Imagine you have two faucets in your bathroom, one for the sink and one for the shower. The temperature <m>T</m> of the water (in degrees Fahrenheit) depends on how many inches <m>x</m> you turn the handle to the left or right. Suppose both faucets have a temperature of <m>70</m> degrees Fahrenheit when the handle is centered (<m>x=0</m>), and the temperature increases as you turn the handle to the right. When you turn the shower handle half an inch to the right, the temperature rises to <m>72</m> degrees Fahrenheit. Hence we can calculate the sensitivity of the shower faucet by finding the <em>ratio</em> between the change in temperature (<m>\Delta T</m>) and the change in handle position (<m>\Delta x</m>):
        </p>
        <md>
            <mrow> \dfrac{\Delta T}{\Delta x} \amp = \dfrac{T\tsub{final} - T\tsub{init}}{x\tsub{final} - x\tsub{init}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \dfrac{72 - 70}{0.5 - 0} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \dfrac{2\text{ degrees Fahrenheit}}{0.5\text{ inches}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = 4\text{ degrees Fahrenheit per inch} </mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
            But when you turn the sink faucet half an inch to the right, the temperature instead rises to <m>74</m> degrees Fahrenheit. Then the sensitivity of the sink faucet would be:
        </p>
        <md>
            <mrow> \dfrac{\Delta T}{\Delta x} \amp = \dfrac{74 - 70}{0.5 - 0} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \dfrac{4\text{ degrees Fahrenheit}}{0.5\text{ inches}} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = 8\text{ degrees Fahrenheit per inch} </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>
            Hence the temperature of the water from the sink is more <term>sensitive</term> than the temperature of the water from the shower when we make changes in the handle position.
        </p>
        
        <p>
            We can get a better understanding of this sensitivity by looking at a graph. Suppose the blue line represents the graph of the shower faucet's temperature, while the red line represents the graph of the sink faucet's temperature.
        </p>
        <image width="75%">
			<prefigure label="faucets" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
				<diagram dimensions="(300,400)" margins="30">
				<coordinates bbox="(-4,0,4,90)">
					<grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="T(x)" h-frame="bottom" />
                    <line p1="(-3,58)" p2="(3,82)" stroke="blue"/>
                    <line p1="(-2,54)" p2="(2,86)" stroke="red"/>
                    <point p="(-3,58)" fill="blue"/>
                    <point p="(-2,54)" fill="red"/>
                    <point p="(3,82)" fill="blue"/>
                    <point p="(2,86)" fill="red"/>
				</coordinates>
				</diagram>
			</prefigure>
		</image>
        <p>
            Notice that the sensitivity we calculated above is the <em>slope</em> of each line segment. The steeper the graph, the more sensitive the dependent variable is to changes in the independent variable.
        </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-sensitivity-of-nonlinear-functions">
        <title>Sensitivity of nonlinear functions</title>
        <p>
            In the example above, the temperature of the water from each faucet was a <term>linear</term> function of the position of each handle, which means that the sensitivity was the same no matter which two points we chose to calculate it between. But what if we analyze a situation where the relationship is <term>nonlinear</term>?
        </p>
        <p>
			Imagine you're organizing a large concert and selling tickets. The revenue <m>R</m> that you earn (in thousands of dollars) is a function of the price <m>p</m> that you charge (in dollars), modeled by the function
			<me>
				R(p) = 4p - 0.25p^2
			</me>.
		</p>
		<aside>
			<p>
				In general, when one quantity depends on another, there are two common ways to name this relationship. We can name the output directly, as in <m>y</m> depending on <m>x</m> and writing <m>y = y(x)</m>, or we can give the function a separate name and write <m>y = f(x)</m>.
			</p>
		</aside>
		<p>
			The graph of revenue according to price is shown below.
		</p>
		<image width="75%">
			<prefigure label="revenue-price" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
				<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="30">
				<definition>f(x)=0.25*x*(16-x)</definition>
				<definition>a = 3</definition>
				<definition>b = 8</definition>
				<coordinates bbox="(0,0,20,20)">
					<grid-axes xlabel="p" ylabel="R(p)" h-frame="bottom" v-frame="left"/>
					<graph at="graph" function="f" domain="(0,16)"/>
					<point p="(a,f(a))" alignment="se"><m>(3,9.75)</m></point>
					<point p="(b,f(b))" alignment="n"><m>(8,16)</m></point>
				</coordinates>
				</diagram>
			</prefigure>
		</image>
		<p>
			For example, since the graph goes through the point <m>(3,9.75)</m>, you know that if you charge a price of <m>\$3.00</m> for your product, your revenue will be <m>R=9.75</m>, that is, <m>\$9,\!750</m>. In function notation, we can write this as <m>R(3)=9.75</m>.
		</p>
        <p>
            Notice the nonlinear shape of the graph of the revenue function:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    At a price of <m>\$0.00</m>, you of course earn no revenue, since you're not charging anything for tickets.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    As the price begins to increase, your revenue increases as well, reaching a maximum of <m>R=16</m> (that is, <m>\$16,\!000</m>) at a price of <m>\$8.00</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    After the price exceeds <m>\$8.00</m>, the revenue starts to decrease, until at a price of <m>\$16.00</m>, consumers are no longer willing to buy tickets, and once again you earn no revenue.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
		<p>
			Now, suppose you're currently charging <m>\$3.00</m>, and you decide to raise the price by <m>\$2.00</m> so that your new price is <m>\$5.00</m>; that is,
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta p \amp = p\tsub{final} - p\tsub{init}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 5 - 3</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 2 \text{ dollars charged}</mrow>
			</md>.
			Then the resulting change in revenue would be
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta R \amp = R\tsub{final} - R\tsub{init}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = R(5) - R(3)</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = (4\cdot 5 - 0.25\cdot 5^2) - (4\cdot 3 - 0.25\cdot 3^2)</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 13.75 - 9.75</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 4 \text{ thousand dollars earned}</mrow>
			</md>.
			Hence the <term>sensitivity</term> of the revenue to this change in price is
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{\Delta R}{\Delta p} \amp = \frac{R(5) - R(3)}{5 - 3}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = \frac{4\text{ thousand dollars earned}}{2\text{ dollars charged}}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 2\text{ thousand dollars earned per dollar charged}</mrow>
			</md>.
		</p>
		<definition>
			<title>Sensitivity between two points</title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					If <m>y=f(x)</m>, then the <term>sensitivity</term> of <m>f</m> between the points <m>x=a</m> and <m>x=b</m> is defined as
					<me>
						\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} = \frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b - a}
					</me>.
					
					That is, the sensitivity is the ratio of the change in the output to the change in the input over that interval. We often say this out loud as <sq>the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to the change in <m>x</m>.</sq>
				</p>
				<p>
					We will also use the notation <m>\dfrac{\Delta f}{\Delta x}</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
		<p>
			However, notice that since our graph is nonlinear, the sensitivity would be different if we had chosen a different pair of points.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use this same process to find the sensitivity when the ticket price changes:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li>
						<p>
							from <m>\$3</m> to <m>\$4</m>
						</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>
							from <m>\$4</m> to <m>\$5</m>
						</p>
					</li>
				</ul>
				<p>
					How do these sensitivites compare to the sensitivity we calculated above when the ticket price changes from <m>\$3</m> to <m>\$5</m>? What do you notice about the relationship between the sensitivity and the shape of the graph?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</activity>
    </subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="subsec-sensitivity-at-a-point">
		<title>Sensitivity at a point</title>
		<p>
			Our calculation of the sensitivity above was somewhat coarse: since the graph of <m>R(p)</m> is curved, the slope gets gradually steeper as we go along the curve. In other words, our calculation seems to mix together several sensitivities.
		</p>
		<p>
			If we want a more fine-grained measurement, a natural idea is to look at smaller changes in price. Here's what happens if we use a change in price of <m>\Delta p=0.1</m> dollars:
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{\Delta R}{\Delta p} \amp = \frac{R(3.1) - R(3)}{3.1-3}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = \frac{0.2475\text{ thousand dollars earned}}{0.1\text{ dollars charged}}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 2.475\text{ thousand dollars earned per dollar charged}</mrow>
			</md>.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Estimate the sensitivity of the revenue to the following changes <m>\Delta p</m> (assuming an initial price of <m>p\tsub{init}=3</m> dollars). What do you notice about the values you get?
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta p=0.01</m> dollars
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta p=0.001</m> dollars
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta p=-0.1</m> dollars
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta p=-0.01</m> dollars
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta p=-0.001</m> dollars
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</activity>
		<p>
			Over smaller and smaller changes, the graph looks more and more like a straight line, and the slope between the two points appears to approach a particular value, which seems to be around <m>2.5</m> thousand dollars earned per dollar charged. (We'll soon learn how to find this value exactly, without having to do so many calculations.)
		</p>
		<p>
			Now, let's ask a bold question: what if we could zoom in <sq>infinitely close</sq> to the point <m>(3,9.75)</m>?
		</p>
		<p>
			If we could do this, we might imagine that the graph of <m>R(p)</m> would be indistinguishable from a perfectly straight line at that point. So if we could somehow choose two points that are <sq>infinitely close</sq> to each other, then the ratio of the infinitesimal (infinitely small) changes would be the slope of that line:
		</p>
		<image width="75%">
			<prefigure label="revenue-price-sensitivity-point" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
				<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="30">
				<definition>f(x)=0.25*x*(16-x)</definition>
				<definition>a = 3</definition>
				<definition>b = 8</definition>
				<coordinates bbox="(0,0,20,20)">
					<grid-axes xlabel="p" ylabel="R(p)" h-frame="bottom" v-frame="left"/>
					<graph at="graph" function="f" domain="(0,16)"/>
					<point p="(a,f(a))"/>
				</coordinates>
				</diagram>
			</prefigure>
		</image>
		<p>
			We call these infinitely small changes <term>differentials</term>, and we represent them with a lowercase <m>\mathrm{d}</m>: in this case, we would write <m>\dd{p}</m> to denote an infinitesimal change in price, and <m>\dd{R}</m> to denote the corresponding infinitesimal change in revenue. The ratio of these differentials would then be written <me>\dv{R}{p}</me>. We will call this the <term>sensitivity</term> <em>at the single point</em> where <m>p=3</m> dollars.
		</p>
		<definition xml:id="def-sensitivity-at-a-point">
			<title>Sensitivity at a point</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If <m>y=f(x)</m>, the <term>sensitivity</term> of <m>f</m> at the point <m>x=a</m> is (for the time being) defined as
					<me>
						\dv{y}{x}\approx\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}
					</me>
					where <m>b</m> is <sq>infinitely close</sq> to <m>a</m>. This definition is currently somewhat vague, as we have not defined what it means to be <sq>infinitely close.</sq> We'll make this definition more precise later.
				</p>
				<p>
					We will also use the notation <m>\DS\dv{f}{x}</m> for this sensitivity.
				</p>
				<p>
					When we want to emphasize that the sensitivity is being evaluated at a particular point <m>x=a</m>, we will write <m>\eval{\DS\dv{y}{x}}_{x=a}</m> or <m>\eval{\DS\dv{f}{x}}_{x=a}</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
		<p>
			Now, you might be a bit skeptical of this idea of using <sq>infinitely small</sq> changes. If so, you're in good company! This idea of using infinitesimal quantities has long been a controversial topic in mathematics. On one hand, infinity is notoriously difficult to get a handle on <mdash/> just how small is <sq>infinitely small</sq> anyway? On the other hand, allowing ourselves to work with these infinitesimal ideas has helped us solve a lot of tricky problems throughout history. By developing calculus, we'll be able to find a way to make these intuitive-but-somewhat-vague arguments more precise, which will allow us to use them with confidence to describe real-world phenomena in a variety of applied contexts.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use this same process to estimate <m>\eval{\DS\dv{R}{p}}_{p=5}</m> and <m>\eval{\DS\dv{R}{p}}_{p=9}</m>. How does the sensitivity of revenue to changes in price compare at these different prices?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</activity>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="subsec-interpreting-sensitivity">
		<title>Interpreting sensitivity</title>
		
		<p>
			We can get some useful information about how the revenue changes with respect to the price by looking at the slope of the graph at each point:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					On the left side of the graph (when <m>p \lt 8</m>), the sensitivity <m>\DS\dv{R}{p}</m> is positive. This means that increasing the price would lead to an increase in revenue, and decreasing the price would lead to a decrease in revenue.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					On the right side of the graph (when <m>p \gt 8</m>), the sensitivity <m>\DS\dv{R}{p}</m> is negative. This means that increasing the price would lead to a <em>decrease</em> in revenue, and decreasing the price would lead to an increase in revenue.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>

		<p>
			So looking at the <em>sign</em> of the sensitivity can tell us the <em>direction</em> in which our function responds to changes. We can also use it to tell <em>how much</em> the revenue will change to a small change in price. For example, suppose that at a price of <m>\$9.00</m>, we know that the sensitivity is <me>\eval{\DS\dv{R}{p}}_{p=9} = -0.5\text{ thousand dollars earned per dollar charged}</me>.
			Now suppose we want to raise the price from <m>\$9.00</m> to <m>\$9.10</m>. Since the sensitivity <m>\DS\dv{R}{p}</m> is supposed to be the ratio of <sq>infinitely small</sq> changes, we can write:
			<me>
				\dfrac{\Delta R}{\Delta p} \approx \DS\dv{R}{p}
			</me>
			Then we can rearrange the terms to get
			<me>
				\Delta R \approx \DS\dv{R}{p}\cdot \Delta p
			</me>.
			Substituting what we know, we have
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta R \amp \approx -0.5\cdot 0.10</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = -0.05\text{ thousand dollars}</mrow>.
			</md>
			Hence if we increase the price from <m>$9.00</m> to <m>$9.10</m>, we can estimate that the revenue will decrease by approximately <m>\$50.00</m>.
		</p>
		<p>
			In this case, we can explicitly calculate the actual change in revenue to see how good our estimate is. We have
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta R \amp = R(9.1) - R(9)</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 15.6975 - 15.75</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = -0.0525\text{ thousand dollars}</mrow>
			</md>.
			So our estimate of a <m>\$50.00</m> decrease in revenue was pretty close to the actual decrease of about <m>\$52.50</m>. However, computing the actual decrease required we compute the revenue at two different prices, and for a different change in price, we'd need to compute a new revenue every single time. Using the sensitivity at a point instead lets us make lots of quick estimates of how the revenue will change in response to small changes in price without having to recompute the revenue every time.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose that we decide to <em>decrease</em> the price from <m>$9.00</m> to <m>$8.95</m>. How much would we estimate the revenue to change? Would it increase or decrease? Use the sensitivity at <m>p=9</m> to justify your answer.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</activity>
	</subsection>

	<exercises>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					In this exercise, you'll interpret the sign of the sensitivity for various real-world contexts. For each one, determine whether the sensitivity should be positive, negative, or zero, and explain your answer. (Think: if you increase the independent variable, what would you expect to happen to the dependent variable?) Also give the units for the sensitivity.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{B}{P}</m>, where <m>B=</m> the brightness of a lamp (measured in lumens) and <m>P=</m> the electrical power supplied to the lamp (measured in watts)
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{S}{D}</m>, where <m>S=</m> the strength of a wireless signal (in bars) and <m>D=</m> the distance from the signal source (in meters)
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{T}{t}</m>, where <m>T=</m> the temperature (in degrees Fahrenheit) of a baked potato and <m>t=</m> the number of minutes for which the potato is left to bake in the oven
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{t}{T}</m>, where <m>t=</m> the number of minutes it takes to fully bake a potato (i.e. to get it to reach a desired temperature) and <m>T=</m> the temperature (in degrees Fahrenheit) of the oven
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{C}{h}</m>, where <m>C=</m> the number of calories in a candy bar and <m>h=</m> the elevation (in feet) of the candy bar above sea level
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>y=3x-2</m>, so <m>y</m> is a <term>linear function</term> of <m>x</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to various changes in <m>x</m> by completing the following table.
					</p>
					<tabular halign="center">
						<row header="yes" bottom="minor">
							<cell><m>x=a</m></cell>
							<cell><m>x=b</m></cell>
							<cell><m>\Delta x</m></cell>
							<cell><m>\Delta y</m></cell>
							<cell><m>\dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</m></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>2</m></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>1.1</m></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>1.01</m></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>0.99</m></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
						</row>
					</tabular>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What do you notice about the values you get for the sensitivity in each case?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What does <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m>, the sensitivity of <m>y</m>, seem to be at the point <m>x=1</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What would be the sensitivity of <m>y</m> at the point <m>x=2</m>? Why? 
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What can you conclude about the sensitivity of <m>y=mx+b</m> at any point <m>x=a</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					It can be shown that in the ticket example, the <term>quantity demanded</term> of tickets (the number of tickets that consumers are willing to buy, measured in thousands of tickets) is a function of the price, given by <m>x(p)=4-0.25p</m>. The revenue is then given by
					<md>
						<mrow>R(p) \amp = p \cdot x(p) </mrow>
						<mrow>\amp = p \cdot (4-0.25p) </mrow>
						<mrow>\amp = 4p - 0.25p^2 </mrow>
					</md>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find <m>\DS\dv{x}{p}</m>, the sensitivity of the quantity demanded to changes in price, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Interpret the value and the sign of the <m>\DS\dv{x}{p}</m> in the context of the problem.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose you raise the price from <m>\$3.00</m> to <m>\$3.10</m>. What will happen to the number of tickets people are willing to buy?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>y=5</m>, so <m>y</m> is a <term>constant function</term> of <m>x</m>. That is, no matter what the value of <m>x</m> is, the value of <m>y</m> is always <m>5</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What will <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> be at any point <m>x=a</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What does the graph of <m>y=5</m> look like? How does this graph help you understand the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to changes in <m>x</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						If we rewrite <m>y</m> as <m>0x+5</m>, how does this help you understand the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to changes in <m>x</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						If <m>y=k</m> is a constant function of <m>x</m>, where <m>k</m> is any constant, what will the sensitivity of <m>y</m> be at any point <m>x=a</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>y=x^2</m>, so <m>y</m> is a <term>quadratic function</term> of <m>x</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> at the point <m>x=1</m> by computing the ratios of small changes in the input and output. As the intervals get smaller and smaller, what number does the sensitivity seem to be approaching?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Repeat the above exercise to estimate <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> at the points <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=3</m>. What do you notice about the values you get for the sensitivity at these different points?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Without doing any calculations, what do you think the sensitivity of <m>y=x^2</m> will be at the point <m>x=0</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Conjecture a formula for <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> at any point <m>x=a</m>. Why do you think this formula is correct?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<title>Extra practice</title>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Estimate <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> for each of the following graphs at the given points by computing the ratios of small changes in the input and output. As the intervals get smaller and smaller, what number do the sensitivities seem to be approaching?
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=x^3</m>, at <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=-1</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=\sqrt{x}</m>, at <m>x=9</m> and <m>x=12</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=\dfrac{1}{x}</m>, at <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=7</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=x^2-5x+4</m>, at <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=4</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose the temperature in the Pacific Ocean can be described by the function <m>T(\ell)</m>, where <m>T</m> is the temperature in degrees Celsius and <m>\ell</m> is the latitude in degrees.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose that <m>T(60)=10</m>. Explain what this means in context, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose that we also know that <m>\eval{\DS\dv{T}{\ell}}_{\ell=60}=-0.5</m>. Explain what this means in context, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate <m>T(62)</m> and <m>T(59)</m> using the sensitivity at <m>\ell=60</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
				The profit earned by a company can be defined as the revenue (the money it brings in) minus the costs (the money it spends). The graph below shows <m>P(x)</m>, the profit (in thousands of dollars) earned by a company as a function of <m>x</m>, the number of units produced (in hundreds of units).
				</p>
				<image width="75%">
					<prefigure label="profit-units" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
						<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
						<definition>P(x)=-0.5*x^2+15*x-40</definition>
						<coordinates bbox="(-5,-50,32,120)">
							<grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="P(x)"/>
							<graph at="graph" function="P" domain="(0,30)"/>
						</coordinates>
						</diagram>
					</prefigure>
				</image>
			</introduction>

			<task>
				<statement>
				<p>
					For which values of <m>x</m> does <m>P(x)</m> appear to be positive? What about negative? Explain how you can tell from the graph. What do these values mean practically for the company?
				</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What are the units of <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
				<p>
					For which values of <m>x</m> does <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m> appear to be positive? What about negative? Explain how you can tell from the graph. What do these values mean practically for the company?
				</p>
				</statement>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
				<p>
					Based on the graph, about how many units should the company produce in order to maximize profit, and what is that maximum profit? What is <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m> at that point?
				</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>

		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					A car is driven along a fixed 100-mile route. The table below shows the total amount of energy <m>E</m> used for the trip as a function of the car's speed <m>v</m>. Here <m>v</m> is measured in miles per hour and <m>E</m> is measured in kilowatt-hours.
				</p>
				<tabular halign="center">
					<row header="yes" bottom="minor">
						<cell right="minor"><m>v \text{ (mph)}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>45</m></cell>
						<cell><m>50</m></cell>
						<cell><m>55</m></cell>
						<cell><m>60</m></cell>
						<cell><m>65</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell right="minor"><m>E \text{ (kWh)}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>32.4</m></cell>
						<cell><m>31.0</m></cell>
						<cell><m>30.6</m></cell>
						<cell><m>30.9</m></cell>
						<cell><m>31.8</m></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate <m>\eval{\DS\dv{E}{v}}_{v=52}</m> and explain its meaning in context, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Use your estimate of <m>\eval{\DS\dv{E}{v}}_{v=52}</m> to estimate the total energy used at <m>v=56</m> mph.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose we know that the energy usage is <em>minimized</em> when <m>v=55</m> mph. What would you expect the value of <m>\DS\dv{E}{v}</m> to be at that speed? Explain.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					How does the sensitivity of <m>y=f(x)</m> from <m>x=a</m> to <m>x=b</m> compare to its sensitivity from <m>x=b</m> to <m>x=a</m>? Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
	</exercises>
</section>

